"Only detects free haemoglobin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUrine dipstick testing uses a peroxidase reaction that \u003Cstrong\u003Edetects both intact red blood cells and free haemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E. This makes it highly sensitive but less specific, as it cannot distinguish between these sources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly detects intact red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The test detects any haem-containing protein, not just intact cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires microscopy for detection of any blood\u003C/strong\u003E - Dipstick testing can detect blood independently; microscopy is used for confirmation and morphology assessment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas high specificity but poor sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E - The opposite is true; the test has high sensitivity but lower specificity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly detects free haemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E - The test detects both free haemoglobin and intact red blood cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFalse positive results can occur from myoglobinuria, haemoglobinuria, or menstrual contamination. Microscopy should be performed to confirm positive dipstick results and assess red cell morphology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Urine dipstick testing detects both intact red blood cells and free haemoglobin through a peroxidase reaction","The test has high sensitivity but lower specificity for haematuria","Microscopy is required to confirm the source and morphology of red blood cells"],"references":["Lim WH, Choi EK, Han KD, Rhee TM, Lee HJ, Lee SR, Kang SH, Cha MJ, Oh S. Proteinuria Detected by Urine Dipstick Test as a Risk Factor for Atrial Fibrillation: A Nationwide Population-Based Study. Sci Rep. 2017 Jul 24;7(1):6324. doi: 10.1038/s41598-017-06579-0. PMID: 28740259; PMCID: PMC5524798.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Leslie SW, Hamawy K, Saleem MO. Gross and Microscopic Hematuria. 2024 Feb 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30480952."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15076"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:19:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:20:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67897"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"